The following index definition indexes the `page_updated_by.email`
field in the `minutes` collection using a custom analyzer named
`basicEmailAddressAnalyzer`. It uses the `uaxUrlEmail` tokenizer to
create tokens (searchable terms) from URL (Uniform Resource Locator)s and email
addresses in the `page_updated_by.email` field.

**Atlas UI:**

Atlas UI

Visual Editor

- In the Custom Analyzers section, click Add
  Custom Analyzer.

- Select the Create Your Own radio button and click
  Next.

- Type whitespace in the Analyzer Name field.

- Expand Tokenizer if it's collapsed.

- Select whitespace from the dropdown.

- Click Add to add the custom analyzer to your index.

- In the Field Mappings section, click Add
  Field Mapping to apply the custom analyzer on the
  message field.

- Select message from the Field
  Name dropdown and dateFacet from the Data
  Type dropdown.

- In the properties section for the data type, select whitespace
  from the Index Analyzer and Search Analyzer
  dropdowns.

- Click Add, then Save Changes.

JSON Editor

Replace the default index definition with the following:

```json
{
  "mappings": {
    "fields": {
      "page_updated_by": {
       "fields": {
          "email": {
            "analyzer": "basicEmailAddressAnalyzer",
            "type": "string"
          }
        },
        "type": "document"
      }
    }
  },
  "analyzers": [
    {
      "name": "basicEmailAddressAnalyzer",
      "tokenizer": {
        "type": "uaxUrlEmail"
      }
    }
  ]
}
```

**Shell:**

MongoDB Shell

```javascript
db.minutes.createSearchIndex("default", {
  "mappings": {
    "fields": {
      "page_updated_by": {
        "fields": {
          "email": {
            "analyzer": "basicEmailAddressAnalyzer",
            "type": "string"
          }
        },
        "type": "document"
      }
    }
  },
  "analyzers": [
    {
      "name": "basicEmailAddressAnalyzer",
      "tokenizer": {
        "type": "uaxUrlEmail"
      }
    }
  ]
})

```

The following query searches the `page_updated_by.email` field in
the `minutes` collection for the email `lewinsky@example.com`.

**Atlas UI:**

Atlas UI

- Click the Query button for your index.

- Click Edit Query to edit the query.

- Click on the query bar and select the database and collection.

- Replace the default query with the following and click
  Find:

  **Input:**

  ```json
  {
    "$search": {
      "text": {
        "query": "lewinsky@example.com",
        "path": "page_updated_by.email"
      }
    }
  }
  ```

  **Output:**

  ```js
  SCORE: 0.5472603440284729   _id:  "3"
   message: "try to sign-in"
     page_updated_by: Object
     last_name: "LEWINSKY"
     first_name: "Brièle"
     email: "lewinsky@example.com"
     phone: "(123).456.9870"
   text: Object
     en_US: "<body>We'll head out to the conference room by noon.</body>"
  ```

**Shell:**

MongoDB Shell

**Input:**

```json
db.minutes.aggregate([
  {
    "$search": {
      "autocomplete": {
        "query": "lewinsky@example.com",
        "path": "page_updated_by.email"
      }
    }
  },
  {
    "$project": {
      "_id": 1,
      "page_updated_by.email": 1
    }
  }
])
```

**Output:**

```js
{ _id: 3, page_updated_by: { email: 'lewinsky@example.com' } }
```

MongoDB Search returns the document with `_id: 3` in the results
because MongoDB Search created a token with the value
`lewinsky@example.com` using the `uaxUrlEmail` tokenizer
for the documents, which matches the search term. If you
index the `page_updated_by.email` field using the
`standard` tokenizer, MongoDB Search returns all the documents for
the search term `lewinsky@example.com`.

The following table shows the tokens that the `uaxUrlEmail`
tokenizer and by comparison, the `standard` tokenizer, create for
the document with `_id: 3`:

| Tokenizer   | Token Outputs         |
| ----------- | --------------------- |
| standard    | lewinsky, example.com |
| uaxUrlEmail | lewinsky\@example.com |

The following index definition indexes the `page_updated_by.email`
field in the `minutes` collection using a custom analyzer named
`emailAddressAnalyzer`. It uses the following:

- The [autocomplete](autocomplete-ref) type with an
  `edgeGram` [tokenization](bson-data-types-autocomplete)

- The `uaxUrlEmail` tokenizer to create tokens (searchable
  terms) from URL (Uniform Resource Locator)s and email addresses

**Atlas UI:**

Atlas UI

Visual Editor

- In the Custom Analyzers section, click Add
  Custom Analyzer.

- Select the Create Your Own radio button and click
  Next.

- Type whitespace in the Analyzer Name field.

- Expand Tokenizer if it's collapsed.

- Select whitespace from the dropdown.

- Click Add to add the custom analyzer to your index.

- In the Field Mappings section, click Add
  Field Mapping to apply the custom analyzer on the
  message field.

- Select message from the Field
  Name dropdown and dateFacet from the Data
  Type dropdown.

- In the properties section for the data type, select whitespace
  from the Index Analyzer and Search Analyzer
  dropdowns.

- Click Add, then Save Changes.

JSON Editor

Replace the default index definition with the following:

```json
{
  "mappings": {
    "fields": {
      "page_updated_by": {
        "fields": {
          "email": {
            "analyzer": "emailAddressAnalyzer",
            "tokenization": "edgeGram",
            "type": "autocomplete"
          }
        },
        "type": "document"
      }
    }
  },
  "analyzers": [
    {
      "name": "emailAddressAnalyzer",
      "tokenizer": {
        "type": "uaxUrlEmail"
      }
    }
  ]
}
```

**Shell:**

MongoDB Shell

```javascript
db.minutes.createSearchIndex("default", {
  "mappings": {
    "fields": {
      "page_updated_by": {
        "fields": {
          "email": {
            "analyzer": "emailAddressAnalyzer",
            "tokenization": "edgeGram",
            "type": "autocomplete"
          }
        },
        "type": "document"
      }
    }
  },
  "analyzers": [
    {
      "name": "emailAddressAnalyzer",
      "tokenizer": {
        "type": "uaxUrlEmail"
      }
    }
  ]
})

```

The following query searches the `page_updated_by.email` field in
the `minutes` collection for the term `exam`.

**Atlas UI:**

Atlas UI

- Click the Query button for your index.

- Click Edit Query to edit the query.

- Click on the query bar and select the database and collection.

- Replace the default query with the following and click
